00:09:07,400 --> 00:09:14,200
And I know it can be really not fun sometimes to look at the fraction of your week that

119
00:09:14,200 --> 00:09:16,560
is taken up by meetings.

120
00:09:16,560 --> 00:09:23,400
However, it's super, super important in collaborations for this continued expectation setting to have

121
00:09:23,400 --> 00:09:24,400
ongoing meetings.

122
00:09:24,400 --> 00:09:30,120
So we always have an onboarding meeting that happens before we start any work.

123
00:09:30,120 --> 00:09:36,560
And this is where we have the initial conversation about expectations of like, okay, we're going

124
00:09:36,600 --> 00:09:38,320
to work together.

125
00:09:38,320 --> 00:09:40,320
What does that look like?

126
00:09:40,320 --> 00:09:42,880
A meeting set aside just for the onboarding meeting.

127
00:09:42,880 --> 00:09:47,720
And then typically, I mean, so we work on projects of lots of different scales.

128
00:09:47,720 --> 00:09:51,760
Sometimes somebody hands us data, we're done with it in two weeks, we give it back, like,

129
00:09:51,760 --> 00:09:56,000
fine, that does not need regularly scheduled meetings for the length of the project.

130
00:09:56,000 --> 00:10:00,480
But many times we were involved in projects that last a heck of a lot longer than that.

131
00:10:00,480 --> 00:10:05,880
And we have regular meetings that may be every other week, that may be every month, that

132
00:10:05,880 --> 00:10:12,200
may be, you know, every quarter, again, depending on the scale and the scope.

133
00:10:12,200 --> 00:10:15,120
But we have something on the calendar.

134
00:10:15,120 --> 00:10:18,560
And before that meeting is done, we have the next thing on the calendar.

135
00:10:18,560 --> 00:10:24,800
And what that helps in doing is making sure that those shared expectations we set in the

136
00:10:24,800 --> 00:10:28,680
beginning, we can continue to communicate about that.

137
00:10:28,680 --> 00:10:30,200
We can share progress.

138
00:10:30,200 --> 00:10:31,960
We have a chance to ask questions.

139
00:10:31,960 --> 00:10:36,000
And we can let people know, like, hey, this is kind of deviating this direction.

140
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,840
How should we correct, like, should we correct course?

141
00:10:38,840 --> 00:10:41,160
Or are we okay going off in that direction?

142
00:10:41,160 --> 00:10:47,600
Like let's change our shared expectations now together, because we have this established

143
00:10:47,600 --> 00:10:53,000
time to do so, rather than surprising people at the end when something has gone in the

144
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:58,320
way that we didn't predict in the beginning.

145
00:10:58,680 --> 00:11:03,000
That onboarding meeting is so critical to just make sure that everything gets off on,

146
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:04,440
like, the right foot.

147
00:11:04,440 --> 00:11:05,440
Absolutely.

148
00:11:05,440 --> 00:11:06,440
Yeah.

149
00:11:06,440 --> 00:11:12,640
And, you know, I will admit, sometimes we end up with multiple onboarding meetings, again,

150
00:11:12,640 --> 00:11:14,600
depending on how things have come to us.

151
00:11:14,600 --> 00:11:18,400
There may be an onboarding meeting that is either, you know, just me and the collaborator

