00:13:36,680 --> 00:13:44,760
So this may not be totally unfamiliar to folks in academia, but Gantt charts,

178
00:13:46,200 --> 00:13:48,440
they can be really, really helpful.

179
00:13:48,440 --> 00:13:55,640
So the idea being it's just a structure of some, you know, unit time going across the top.

180
00:13:55,640 --> 00:13:58,920
This we have in weeks, it can be months, it can be quarters.

181
00:13:59,160 --> 00:14:09,080
But having some idea going along in a timeframe of what is the task that needs to be done,

182
00:14:09,080 --> 00:14:12,040
and over what chunk of time will it be done.

183
00:14:14,040 --> 00:14:19,160
This can then make very clear, you know, they have to putting this together can make clear.

184
00:14:19,160 --> 00:14:25,720
Oh, if they want us to get done with our work by the end of week four, they really need to get us

185
00:14:26,680 --> 00:14:30,600
the data in week one, because this is how long the components take.

186
00:14:32,120 --> 00:14:39,320
And it can also make clear things like, oh yeah, you know, pink task and blue task actually can

187
00:14:39,320 --> 00:14:40,360
be done at the same time.

188
00:14:40,920 --> 00:14:48,200
So since the priority of this project is speed, maybe I have a postdoc working on the pink task

